---
// Author: Bubba (Claude Sonnet 4.6)
// Date: 2026-03-22
// PURPOSE: Voynich Manuscript museum-experience page for VoynichLabs website.
//          Not a Wikipedia summary — a hushed, atmospheric exhibit. The visitor should
//          feel the genuine vertigo of a 600-year-old mystery that no technology has cracked.
// SRP/DRY check: Pass - single responsibility per page, shared Base layout reused
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const worlds = [
  {
    emoji: '🌿',
    name: 'The Herbal World',
    folio: 'f2v',
    image: '/voynich/f2v-herbal.jpg',
    question: 'We have botanical encyclopedias from this same era. We can identify every plant in them. Not one plant in this section has ever been matched to a real species.',
  },
  {
    emoji: '⭐',
    name: 'The Sky World',
    folio: 'f68r3',
    image: '/voynich/f68r3-astronomical.jpg',
    question: 'The zodiac signs are recognizable. But the text, the figures, the arrangement — nothing matches any known astrological system from any culture.',
  },
  {
    emoji: '🧘',
    name: 'The Bathing World',
    folio: 'f77v',
    image: '/voynich/f77v-biological.jpg',
    question: 'Rows of small figures in pools connected by pipes and tubes. Anatomical? Cosmological? A medical tradition we've lost entirely? Nobody agrees.',
  },
  {
    emoji: '🌍',
    name: 'The Map World',
    folio: 'f86v',
    image: '/voynich/f86v-cosmological.jpg',
    question: 'The largest page in the manuscript — six folios wide. Castles, circles, landmasses. A map of the cosmos? A real place? An allegory? Unknown.',
  },
  {
    emoji: '💊',
    name: 'The Pharmacy',
    folio: 'f99r',
    image: '/voynich/f99r-pharmaceutical.jpg',
    question: 'Jars, roots, containers — clearly a pharmacopoeia. But a pharmacopoeia of what? For what illness? For whom?',
  },
];

const openQuestions = [
  {
    q: 'Who wrote it?',
    a: 'Unknown. Candidates have included Roger Bacon (ruled out by carbon dating), Wilfrid Voynich himself as a hoax (unlikely given the pigment analysis), and dozens of others. None confirmed.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What language is it?',
    a: 'Unknown. Statistical analysis shows properties of natural language — consistent entropy, word frequencies matching Zipf\'s law — but it matches no known human language. Not a cipher of Latin. Not Arabic, Hebrew, or any Eastern script.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is it about?',
    a: 'Unknown. The sections suggest medicine, astronomy, botany, and cosmology. But this could be decorative, symbolic, or entirely misleading.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Was it made in Europe?',
    a: 'Probably. The vellum is European. The pigments are European. The binding style is European. The content is not recognizably European.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it a hoax?',
    a: 'Possibly — but the effort required would have been extraordinary. A 240-page hand-illustrated fabrication in 1420, for a nonexistent audience? To what end?',
  },
  {
    q: 'Has AI solved it?',
    a: 'No. Not even close. Large language models trained on every known human language have been applied to the Voynich text. No match. No statistical overlap that unlocks it.',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="The Voynich Manuscript"
  description="A museum experience — the most mysterious book in the world, and the namesake of VoynichLabs."
>
  <!-- Opening Hook: Three questions before the title -->
  <section class="relative min-h-screen flex items-center justify-center overflow-hidden">
    <div
      class="absolute inset-0 bg-cover bg-center bg-no-repeat scale-105"
      style="background-image: url('/voynich/f1r-opening.jpg'); filter: blur(1px);"
    ></div>
    <div class="absolute inset-0" style="background: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0,0,0,0.85) 0%, rgba(10,8,6,0.92) 100%);"></div>
    <div class="relative z-10 text-center max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-32">
      <div class="space-y-6 mb-16" style="color: #c8b89a;">
        <p class="text-xl sm:text-2xl leading-relaxed italic" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">Someone wrote this.</p>
        <p class="text-xl sm:text-2xl leading-relaxed italic" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">They knew what it meant.</p>
        <p class="text-xl sm:text-2xl leading-relaxed italic" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">Everyone who has tried to read it since — cryptographers, linguists, AI systems, you — has failed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="w-24 h-px mx-auto mb-12 opacity-40" style="background-color: #c8b89a;"></div>
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-4 opacity-60" style="color: #c8b89a;">c. 1404–1438 · Beinecke MS 408</p>
      <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-7xl font-bold mb-6 leading-tight tracking-tight" style="font-family: 'Georgia', 'Times New Roman', serif; color: #f5e6c8;">
        The Voynich<br/>Manuscript
      </h1>
      <p class="text-base opacity-60" style="color: #c8b89a; font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">Our namesake.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Object -->
  <section class="py-24 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">The Object</p>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-10 text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
      What it actually is
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-text-secondary">
      <p>
        240 pages of vellum — calfskin, made between 1404 and 1438. Each page roughly 23 × 16 cm.
        The ink is iron gall, the same ink used across medieval Europe for centuries. The pigments —
        greens, blues, reds — are consistent with the period, derived from plants and minerals.
        Nothing unusual. Nothing exotic.
      </p>
      <p>
        The script flows left to right, with clear word spacing and consistent letter forms.
        It looks <em class="text-text-primary">fluent</em>. Someone wrote this the way you write your native language —
        with the ease of a person who has written it ten thousand times before.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed" style="color: #f5e6c8; font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
        The script has never matched any known language. In any database. In any century of analysis.
        Not a cipher of Latin. Not Arabic, Hebrew, or any Eastern script.
        Not a constructed language from the period. Nothing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We've Tried: Recent Science -->
  <section class="py-20 border-y border-border" style="background: rgba(20,16,12,0.6);">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">What We've Tried</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-12 text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
        Six centuries of failure
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-12">
        <div class="border-l-2 pl-8" style="border-color: rgba(200, 184, 154, 0.3);">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3" style="color: #c8b89a; opacity: 0.7;">2024 · Multispectral Imaging</p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3">
            Researchers using X-ray fluorescence and multispectral imaging found something extraordinary
            on the first folio: three columns of lettering, invisible to the naked eye.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed" style="color: #f5e6c8; font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
            They appear to be the work of Jacobus de Tepenec — the Prague physician who owned the manuscript
            around 1608. He was trying to decode it. He failed.
            We found his failed attempt six centuries later with ultraviolet light.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 pl-8" style="border-color: rgba(200, 184, 154, 0.3);">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3" style="color: #c8b89a; opacity: 0.7;">2022 · Yale Statistical Study</p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            Gaskell and Bowern showed human participants glyphs from the manuscript and found people
            could reproduce its statistical patterns — consistent letter distributions, word spacing rules,
            positional constraints. The script behaves like a natural language. It obeys Zipf's law.
            It has structure. It is <em class="text-text-primary">not random noise</em>. And still it yields nothing.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 pl-8" style="border-color: rgba(200, 184, 154, 0.3);">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3" style="color: #c8b89a; opacity: 0.7;">2023–2025 · AI Analysis</p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            Large language models trained on every documented human language have been applied to the
            Voynich text. Every known cipher system has been tested against it. Every statistical
            fingerprint of every known writing system has been compared to it.
            No match. No overlap that unlocks it. The most powerful language tools ever built
            have looked at this manuscript and come away empty.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Five Worlds -->
  <section class="py-24">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">The Manuscript</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
        Five worlds inside
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-16 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        The manuscript is organized into sections — each with its own visual logic, its own mysteries.
        A sixth section consists entirely of dense text with no illustrations: the "Recipes" — the most
        promising for linguistic analysis, the most opaque in meaning.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-0">
        {worlds.map((world, i) => (
          <div
            class={`grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-0 border border-border ${i > 0 ? 'border-t-0' : ''}`}
            key={world.folio}
          >
            <div class={`relative aspect-video lg:aspect-auto overflow-hidden ${i % 2 === 1 ? 'lg:order-2' : ''}`}>
              <img
                src={world.image}
                alt={`Voynich Manuscript — ${world.name}, folio ${world.folio}`}
                class="w-full h-full object-cover opacity-85 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity duration-500"
                style="min-height: 320px;"
                loading="lazy"
              />
              <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 p-4">
                <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded" style="background: rgba(0,0,0,0.7); color: #c8b89a; opacity: 0.8;">{world.folio}</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class={`flex flex-col justify-center p-10 lg:p-16 ${i % 2 === 1 ? 'lg:order-1' : ''}`} style="background: rgba(16,12,8,0.8);">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
                <span class="text-2xl">{world.emoji}</span>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">{world.name}</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-base leading-relaxed" style="color: #c8b89a; font-family: 'Georgia', serif; font-style: italic; font-size: 1.05rem;">
                {world.question}
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Open Questions Wall -->
  <section class="py-24 border-y border-border" style="background: rgba(14,11,8,0.8);">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">Provenance</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
        What we still don't know
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-14 leading-relaxed">
        After 600 years. After X-rays, UV light, AI, and the world's best cryptographers.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-10">
        {openQuestions.map((item) => (
          <div class="border-b border-border pb-10 last:border-0 last:pb-0" key={item.q}>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-text-primary" style="font-family: 'Georgia', serif;">
              {item.q}
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">{item.a}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Gallery -->
  <section class="py-20 max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">The Folios</p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-5 gap-2">
      {worlds.map((world) => (
        <a
          href="https://beinecke.library.yale.edu/collections/highlights/voynich-manuscript"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="group relative aspect-[3/4] overflow-hidden bg-black border border-border hover:border-amber-400/30 transition-all duration-300"
          key={`gallery-${world.folio}`}
          title={`Folio ${world.folio} — ${world.name}`}
        >
          <img
            src={world.image}
            alt={`Folio ${world.folio}`}
            class="w-full h-full object-cover opacity-70 group-hover:opacity-95 group-hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-500"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 right-0 p-2" style="background: linear-gradient(transparent, rgba(0,0,0,0.8));">
            <span class="font-mono text-xs" style="color: #c8b89a; opacity: 0.8;">{world.folio}</span>
          </div>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="mt-6 text-sm text-text-muted">
      All images from the Yale Beinecke Library digital collection, public domain.{' '}
      <a href="https://beinecke.library.yale.edu/collections/highlights/voynich-manuscript" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="hover:text-text-primary underline underline-offset-2 transition-colors">
        Browse the full manuscript →
      </a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Why We Named Ourselves After It -->
  <section class="py-20 border-t border-border">
    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-10 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">Why the name</p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-text-secondary mb-8">
        We build systems that try to make planning legible — to take an intention and turn it into
        something structured and actionable.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed" style="color: #f5e6c8; font-family: 'Georgia', serif; font-style: italic;">
        The Voynich Manuscript is a reminder that structure and legibility are not the same thing.
        Something can be deeply structured and completely illegible.
        We think about that.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-12 pt-12 border-t border-border">
        <p class="text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
          VoynichLabs takes its name from Wilfrid Voynich, the rare book dealer who acquired this
          manuscript in 1912 from a Jesuit villa in Frascati, Italy, and brought it to the world's attention.
          The manuscript has lived at Yale's Beinecke Rare Book &amp; Manuscript Library since 1969.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- See It Yourself -->
  <section class="py-16 border-t border-border">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-8 opacity-50" style="color: #c8b89a;">See It Yourself</p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        <a
          href="https://beinecke.library.yale.edu/collections/highlights/voynich-manuscript"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-6 border border-border hover:border-amber-400/30 transition-colors duration-200 group"
          style="background: rgba(16,12,8,0.6);"
        >
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3 opacity-60" style="color: #c8b89a;">Yale Beinecke</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed group-hover:text-text-primary transition-colors">
            The official digital collection. Every folio, high resolution.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Voynich_manuscript"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-6 border border-border hover:border-amber-400/30 transition-colors duration-200 group"
          style="background: rgba(16,12,8,0.6);"
        >
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3 opacity-60" style="color: #c8b89a;">Wikimedia Commons</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed group-hover:text-text-primary transition-colors">
            Full image set organized by section. Public domain.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://archive.org/details/TheVoynichManuscript"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-6 border border-border hover:border-amber-400/30 transition-colors duration-200 group"
          style="background: rgba(16,12,8,0.6);"
        >
          <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider mb-3 opacity-60" style="color: #c8b89a;">Internet Archive</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed group-hover:text-text-primary transition-colors">
            Full manuscript PDF and image download.
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
